{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628531"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:57:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:57:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17221"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17221"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.06,0.26,0,0.61]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9911"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76233"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9911"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17221"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61737"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1251"},{"type":"tags","id":"1418"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"},{"type":"tags","id":"4886"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23245"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23248"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76233"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset right-sided weakness and difficulty speaking that began 90 minutes ago. She has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes, and atrial fibrillation. Her medications include metformin, perindopril, and warfarin. She is a current smoker with a 40 pack-year history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears alert but distressed. Her pulse rate is 88/min and irregular, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. She has expressive dysphasia, right-sided facial droop, and right-sided hemiparesis (power 2/5 in both upper and lower limbs). Her International Normalised Ratio is 1.8 (2.0-3.0).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Idiopathic intracranial hypertension","Subarachnoid haemorrhage","Haemorrhagic stroke","Venous sinus thrombosis","Ischaemic stroke"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with sudden onset focal neurological deficits typical of stroke, with multiple risk factors including hypertension, diabetes, smoking, and poorly controlled atrial fibrillation. \u003Cstrong\u003EIschaemic stroke\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis, given this patients risk factors and given that the majority of strokes are ischaemic in nature \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemorrhagic stroke\u003C/strong\u003E often presents with headache and a decreased level of consciousness in addition to focal deficits. While possible, it is less likely given both that the patient is on subtherapeutic warfarin, and that haemorrhagic stroke is less common that ischaemic stroke accounting for 20% of stroke presentations. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubarachnoid haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with thunderclap headache as the predominant symptom, often described as the worst headache a patient has ever experienced. Focal neurological deficits are less common initially.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenous sinus thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with gradual onset headache and signs of increased intracranial pressure. Focal deficits can occur but are typically not the presenting feature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic intracranial hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E presents with chronic headache, visual symptoms, and papilloedema. It typically affects young, overweight women and does not cause focal neurological deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of multiple vascular risk factors (hypertension, diabetes, smoking, atrial fibrillation), along with the sudden onset of focal neurological deficits without headache, strongly supports ischaemic stroke as the diagnosis. The subtherapeutic INR despite warfarin therapy for atrial fibrillation further increases the risk of cardioembolic stroke.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sudden onset focal neurological deficits without headache are characteristic of ischemic stroke.","Risk factors for ischemic stroke include hypertension, diabetes, smoking, and atrial fibrillation","The majority of strokes are ischaemic in nature, followed by haemorrhagic strokes"],"references":["Tadi P, Lui F. Acute Stroke. [Updated 2023 Aug 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK535369/","Harriott AM, Karakaya F, Ayata C. Headache after ischemic stroke: A systematic review and meta-analysis. Neurology. 2020 Jan 7;94(1):e75-e86. doi: 10.1212/WNL.0000000000008591. Epub 2019 Nov 6. PMID: 31694924; PMCID: PMC7011689.","Xie X, Zhang Y, Kong Q, Huang H, Yu Z, Luo X, Qu W. Current Knowledge about Headaches Attributed to Ischemic Stroke: Changes from Structure to Function. Brain Sci. 2023 Jul 23;13(7):1117. doi: 10.3390/brainsci13071117. PMID: 37509047; PMCID: PMC10377604."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"da